Over the last 7 days, 244 359, 35 418, 27 455, 12 687, 39 205, and 512 COVID-19 cases were detected in India, Bangladesh, Pakistan, Nepal, Sri Lanka, and Afghanistan, respectively, compared with 241 003, 50 342, 26 973, 16 459, 28 047, and 678 in the preceding 7 days, revealing a slightly upward trend again in India, a sharp declining trend in Bangladesh, a slightly increasing trend in Pakistan, a decreasing trend in Nepal, a stable trend with a low number of newly detected cases in Afghanistan, but skyrocketing of the already developed peak with more and more new cases in Sri Lanka.

Live Situational Analysis on COVID-19 cases in Sri Lanka can be seen at https://hpb.health.gov.lk/covid19-dashboard/. The number of daily laboratory-confirmed cases has crossed the mark of 4000 in the country, as indicated in item [E] above, and the number of daily deaths has also crossed the mark of 200. Over the last 24 hours, a total of 209 people died of COVID-19 (https://hpb.health.gov.lk/covid19-dashboard/) in the country. To curb the spread of the virus, the country has imposed a 10-day long nationwide lockdown from the night of 20 Aug 2021 to 30 Aug 2021 (https://www.reuters.com/world/asia-pacific/sri-lankans-seek-full-covid-lockdown-ahead-presidents-address-2021-08-20/), which could be extended further.

There is no clear picture yet that a slight increase of new cases over the course of the last 7 days in Pakistan would turn into the development of a bigger new wave in the country due to the spread of the delta variant. According to data as of 17 Aug 2021 at 11:41 AM, around 50 985 184 doses of COVID-19 vaccines have been administered in the country (https://ncoc.gov.pk/covid-vaccination-en.php).

The daily-case positivity and number of deaths associated with COVID-19 are dropping sharply in Bangladesh. The current case positivity rate is around 14%, as indicated in item [A] above, around 4% lower compared to the rate observed in the preceding week. The total number of deaths attributed to COVID-19 exceeded the milestone of 25 000 in the country. However, there is an indication that the daily number of deaths associated with the disease would fall below 100 soon, as a total of 102 people died yesterday (26 Aug 2021). Bangladesh has a plan of vaccinating 80% population above the age of 18 years. So far, of the target population, only 15% have received the 1st dose and 6% have received both 1st and 2nd doses (http://103.247.238.92/webportal/pages/covid19-vaccination-update.php).

There is now an alarming sign in India that new cases started creeping up over the last 7 days, although counts predominantly from 2 states, Kerala and Maharashtra, contributed largely to see this upward trend after a slow but persistent downward trend over a significant period of time. Only time will say whether this temporal increase will again turn into the development of a new wave in the country. Over 600 million doses of the COVID-19 vaccine have been administered so far in India (https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/india-vaccinations-cross-60-crore-doses-32-coverage-at-this-rate-by-december-2518423#pfrom=home-coronavirus_coronavirus-lateststories_live).

To compare the situation in South Asian countries above with previous disease data, ProMED readers are referred to the ProMED-SoAs archives below:
